✅ Step-by-Step: Setup H2 on Windows (Corporate Safe)

📥 Step 1: Download (If site is blocked)

If the official H2 site is blocked, use one of these options:

Option A (Preferred)

Ask your colleague to share:

h2-2.x.x.jar file


Option B

Download from Maven Central: 👉 https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/com/h2database/h2/

Download latest .jar (example: h2-2.2.224.jar)

👉 This usually works even on restricted networks.


---

📁 Step 2: Place JAR in a Fixed Location

Create a folder:

C:\dev-tools\h2\

Put the jar there:

C:\dev-tools\h2\h2-2.2.224.jar


---

▶️ Step 3: Run H2 Console

Open Command Prompt:

cd C:\dev-tools\h2
java -jar h2-2.2.224.jar

👉 You should see:

“H2 Console available at http://localhost:8082”



---

🌐 Step 4: Open Console

Open browser manually:

http://localhost:8082


---

🔐 Step 5: Login Settings (IMPORTANT)

Use this (best for our app):

JDBC URL: jdbc:h2:file:C:/dev-tools/h2/devworkbench
User: sa
Password: (leave empty)

👉 This creates a persistent database file (not temporary)


---

🧪 Step 6: Verify Setup

Run:

CREATE TABLE snippet (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    title VARCHAR(255),
    code CLOB
);

SELECT * FROM snippet;

If no errors → ✅ Done


---

🧠 Important for Corporate Environment

No server install needed ✔

No admin rights needed ✔

Works offline ✔

No ports except localhost ✔


👉 Safe for corporate machines


---

⚙️ Step 7: Setup in IntelliJ (NO Maven Needed)

Since network may block dependencies, we’ll go manual JAR setup.

Add H2 JAR to Project:

1. Open your project in IntelliJ IDEA Community Edition


2. Go to:

File → Project Structure → Libraries


3. Click + → Java


4. Select:

C:\dev-tools\h2\h2-2.2.224.jar


5. Apply → OK




---

🧱 Step 8: Test DB Connection (Java Code)

Create a test class:

import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;

public class TestDB {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(
                "jdbc:h2:file:C:/dev-tools/h2/devworkbench",
                "sa",
                ""
            );
            System.out.println("Connected to H2 DB!");
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

Run it → You should see:

Connected to H2 DB!


